body:
Consider the following SV input:
```systemverilog
module Foo (input [7:0] a, output [7:0] u, output [7:0] v, output [7:0] w);
  assign {u[7:4], u[3:0]} = a;
  assign {v[4+:4], v[0+:4]} = a;
  assign {w[7-:4], w[3-:4]} = a;
endmodule
```
Round-tripping this produces the following:
```systemverilog
// circt-verilog input.sv | circt-opt --export-verilog -o /dev/null
module Foo(input  [7:0] a, output [7:0] u, v, w);
  wire [3:0] _a_7to4;
  assign _a_7to4 = a[7:4];
  assign u = a;
  assign v = a;
  assign w = {a[1:0], 6'h0} | {2'h0, _a_7to4, 2'h0};
endmodule
```
The last line, `assign w = ...` should also read `assign w = a;`.

The problematic lines in ImportVerilog are at https://github.com/llvm/circt/blob/main/lib/Conversion/ImportVerilog/Expressions.cpp#L1065-L1087. There is quite a bit of duplication between the Rvalue and Lvalue paths, except for the final MLIR op being created. The `IndexedDown` case seems to compute wrong indices here. Worth looking into, and potentially simplifying and joining the Rvalue and Lvalue paths.

